## 5. Design notes & alternatives

| Design choice | Rationale |
|---------------|-----------|
| **Custom block for the handle** | Guarantees deterministic finalisation (the C++ `Reader` is deleted when the OCaml value dies) and hides the C++ pointer from the OCaml world. |
| **Two iteration APIs (push & pull)** | The most ergonomic for OCaml users is `iter`, but some libraries (e.g. Lwt, Async) prefer a pull‑based source; `next` makes that easy. |
| **Pass a closure to C** | Simpler for the OCaml programmer than exposing the raw iterator; the stub does the heavy lifting and ensures the callback runs in the OCaml runtime. |
| **Release the runtime during I/O** | Prevents the whole OCaml program from being blocked while the underlying file is read.  The pattern `caml_release_runtime_system` / `caml_acquire_runtime_system` is safe as long as we do not hold OCaml values across the release (we only keep primitive C++ data). |
| **Exception propagation** | If the user‑supplied OCaml function raises, the stub lets the exception unwind; the iteration stops and the exception is visible to the caller. |
| **No direct exposure of the C++ iterator** | Keeping the C++ type opaque avoids the need for a separate “iterator” OCaml value and sidesteps the difficulty of representing a C++ class hierarchy in the OCaml heap. |
| **Alternative: expose the iterator as an OCaml custom block** | If you need finer‑grained control (e.g. pause/resume), you could add a second custom type representing the iterator and expose `has_next` / `next` methods. The skeleton above can be extended accordingly. |

Feel free to adapt the stub to the exact API that your version of **libpcapng** provides (method names, return types, etc.). The core ideas—custom block for the handle, conversion of a C++ `Frame` into an OCaml record, and a callback loop that releases the runtime—remain the same. Happy hacking!
